ity; however, racial hostility continues to affect Asian American students, and they have actively challenged their invisibility in minority student discussions. This study details the history of Asian American student activism at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, as students rejected the university’s definition of minority student needs that relied on a model minority myth, measures of under-representation, and a Black-White racial model, concepts that made them an “unseen unheard minority.” This activism led to the creation on campus of one of the largest Asian American Studies programs and Asian American cultural centers in the Midwest. Their histories reveal the limitations of understanding minority student needs solely along measures of under-representation and the realities of race for Asian American college students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAsian American college studentsxEthnic identityzIllinoiszChampaign. 0aAsian American college studentsxSocial conditionszIllinoiszChampaign. 0aAsian American college studentszIllinoiszChampaignxEthnic identity. 0aAsian American college studentszIllinoiszChampaignxSocial conditions. 0aStudent movementszIllinoiszChampaignxHistoryy20th century. 0aStudent movementszIllinoiszChampaignxHistoryy21st century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aAsian, American, model minority, diversity, education, model minority myth, under-representation, black-white, Asian American Studies, race, Asian college students, student services, higher education, cultural values, political passivity.1 aLott, Joy Williamson-.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook packag